Female macroptera . Body brown, apex of antennal segment II and antennal segments III–IX all yellow; all tarsi and distal part of tibiae pale, fore wings with posterior margin dark (the dark marking strikingly narrowed at middle) except for basal quarter (including clavus) and distal fifth which are pale, with one sub-basal transverse dark band (
Fig. 3
). Antennae 9 -segmented, segment III with linear sensorium about 0.3 as long as segment, IV with linear sensorium about 0.5 as long as segment and a little curved and wider at the apex, V–IX forming a single unit with V about as long as VI–IX, IX slightly shorter than VIII (
Fig. 7
). Head a little wider than long (
Fig. 1
), with no long setae and weak, irregular, transverse striations; 12–16 pre-ocellar setae present, post-ocellar area with about 30 setae; checks convex; compound eyes prolonged ventrally, with no large or pigmented facets; maxillary palps 3 - segmented. Pronotum with weak transverse striations, with about 50 discal setae, five to six pairs of pronotal posteromarginal setae present that are stouter than pronotal discal setae (
Fig. 1
). Mesonotum transversely striate with pair of median setae. Metanotum with equiangular and longitudinal reticulations medially and laterally respectively (
Fig. 2
). Mesosternum and metasternum with well developed spinula. Abdominal tergites gradually wider towards posterior; tergite I with few striations anteriorly, II–X with weak transverse striations, II–VIII with paired campaniform sensilla posterolateral to median setae; tergite IX setae S 1 about as long as length of tergite. Sternite II with 3 pairs of posteromarginal setae, III–VII with 4 pairs of which the two lateral pairs are sub-marginal (
Fig. 4
); all abdominal sternites without discal setae, sternite VII with 2 pairs of sub-median accessory (“supernumerary paired setae” in Hoddle et al . 2013 ) setae, arranged one in front of the other (
Fig. 4
) and with pair of anterolateral campaniform sensilla.

